{
    "analysis": "From the previous step we have computed global P95 thresholds for every (component, KPI) time series across metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv and stored them in kernel variables metric_thresholds, trace_thresholds, and log_thresholds. The P95 tables show large p95 values for some Redis and Tomcat memory KPIs and high trace row_count p95 for Tomcat/IG components. To locate the failure we must now extract telemetry restricted to the incident time window (March 10, 2021 14:00 — 14:30, system timezone UTC+8) and detect anomalies vs the precomputed global P95 thresholds. This will let us narrow candidate faulty components and times before digging into traces and logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv to the incident window March 10, 2021 14:00 — 14:30 (use UTC+8 handling in code). Restrict components to the allowed root-cause list: [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. Save the filtered full tables into kernel variables named window_metric, window_trace, window_log, window_error_logs. Then, for each of the three filtered tables (window_metric, window_trace, window_log) join with the corresponding thresholds table (metric_thresholds, trace_thresholds, log_thresholds) on (component, kpi_name) and detect anomaly points where value >= p95_value (for metrics/traces/log numeric KPIs). Produce a compact summary table for each (up to top 20 rows) with columns: component, kpi_name, count_points_in_window, count_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (timestamp of first anomaly), max_value_in_window, p95_value, max_value_over_p95 = max_value_in_window / p95_value (use inf or a large number if p95_value==0). Sort rows by count_anomalies descending then by max_value_over_p95 descending. Return these three compact summary tables. Also return the first 20 rows of window_error_logs (component, timestamp, message) for context. Do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "You have already computed global P95 thresholds and filtered telemetry to the incident window (2021-03-10 14:00–14:30 UTC+8). From the compact anomaly summaries: \n- Many metric and log “anomalies” are artifacts caused by p95_value == 0 (resulting in inf ratios); these should be treated as non-actionable unless they show non-zero maxima. \n- Traces show real, substantive anomalies: MG01 and MG02 (trace.self.duration_p95 and various trace.from_/trace.to_ duration_p95 and row_count KPIs) exceed global P95 substantially (ratios ~2.1–2.6) with earliest anomalies clustered around 14:08–14:19; Tomcat nodes (Tomcat01, Tomcat03) also show trace duration spikes around 14:08–14:09. \n- Logs show modest GC pause spikes on Tomcat04 (~14:08) and smaller GC increases on Tomcat03/Tomcat01; log.error_count fields are zeros and not useful. \nWhat can be derived so far: traces point to a performance degradation that impacts MG01/MG02 and several Tomcat endpoints between ~14:08 and ~14:19; logs indicate GC activity on Tomcat nodes (notably Tomcat04 at 14:08) that could explain some latency. We still need to (1) pinpoint the earliest fault start (first consecutive anomaly) among candidate component-KPIs, (2) identify which faulty component is the most downstream faulty service within affected traces, and (3) check logs/metrics on that component to pick a root reason (e.g., GC / JVM OOM / CPU / memory / network).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace anomaly summary stored in the kernel, produce a focused list of candidate trace-faults by selecting rows with count_anomalies >= 2 and max_value_over_p95 > 1.8. Return up to top 20 rows sorted by max_value_over_p95 descending. Include these columns: component, kpi_name, count_points_in_window, count_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95_value, max_value_over_p95. Then, for the top 3 candidates (highest max_value_over_p95), retrieve the specific anomaly timepoints from window_trace where value >= p95_value: return for each candidate up to 10 rows with columns (component, trace_name, timestamp, value). Keep outputs compact (limit rows) and store results in kernel variables named prioritized_trace_faults and prioritized_trace_anomaly_points for follow-up steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor returned focused trace-fault candidates: multiple high-severity trace duration and row_count spikes centered on MG01 and MG02, with earliest substantial anomalies at ~2021-03-10 14:09:00+08 and additional spikes around 14:19:00+08 (and one Tomcat03 self-duration spike at 14:08). Top candidates (by max_value_over_p95) are MG01.trace.to_dockerA1.duration_p95 (14:09 & 14:19) and MG02.trace.from_dockerA2.duration_p95 / MG02.trace.from_dockerB2.duration_p95 (14:09 & 14:19/14:26). Interpretation so far: a performance degradation propagated through MG01/MG02 around 14:08–14:19 affecting calls involving dockerA/B and some Tomcat services. We still need to confirm which component (MG node vs Tomcat) is the actual root cause and whether the reason is resource exhaustion (CPU/memory/GC), network, or disk. Per the diagnosis workflow, the next step is metric analysis focused on the candidate components to discover resource-level anomalies that temporally precede or coincide with the trace spikes. We must first enumerate which metric KPIs exist for these candidate components so we can target the right resource KPIs (CPU, memory, JVM, network, disk, etc.).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv (use full available data, no time filtering), list available KPI groups for components: MG01, MG02, Tomcat01, Tomcat03, Tomcat04. Aggregate by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and return a compact table with columns: component, kpi_name, count, min, median_p50, p95, max. Sort rows by component then p95_value descending. Return up to 50 rows and store the full result in kernel variable selected_metric_groups."
}

{
    "analysis": "The last Executor step returned the available metric KPI groups for the priority components MG01, MG02, Tomcat01, Tomcat03, and Tomcat04 (full-series aggregates with P50/P95/etc.). What has been done: we inspected which KPIs exist on the likely-impacted components after trace analysis pointed to MG01/MG02 and some Tomcats (spikes at ~14:09 and ~14:19). What can be derived: MG nodes expose JVM memory and host CPU/disk/network KPIs; Tomcats expose JVM metrics and request/session KPIs. Traces indicate latency spikes on MG01/MG02 around 14:09 and 14:19. To localize the root cause we now need metric-level 'fault' detection (consecutive significant anomalies) on these candidate components during the incident window to see which resource fault precedes or coincides with trace spikes (and to determine the earliest fault time).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using kernel variables metric_thresholds and window_metric, detect metric-level faults for components [MG01, MG02, Tomcat01, Tomcat03, Tomcat04] within the incident window. For each (component, kpi_name) series do the following: (1) join the window series with metric_thresholds to obtain p95_value per series; (2) mark points where value >= p95_value as anomalous; (3) identify consecutive anomalous runs (faults) and keep only runs with length >= 2; (4) for each run compute: component, kpi_name, run_start_timestamp, run_end_timestamp, run_length, max_value_in_run, p95_value, max_over_p95 = max_value_in_run / p95_value (treat p95_value==0 carefully, show 'inf'); (5) filter to runs where max_over_p95 > 1.5 (significant breach). Return up to top 20 fault runs sorted by max_over_p95 descending then run_length descending. Store full results in kernel variable metric_faults and return the compact table."}

{
    "analysis": "What has been done: we computed global P95 thresholds, filtered telemetry to the incident window (2021-03-10 14:00–14:30 UTC+8), detected anomalies and fault runs. Traces show strong latency spikes on MG01 and MG02 (many trace.duration_p95 and row_count KPI breaches) with earliest substantial MG anomalies at ~14:09 and additional spikes ~14:19–14:26. A Tomcat-level trace (Tomcat03 trace.self.duration_p95) shows an earlier spike at ~14:08. Metric-level fault detection for MG and Tomcat components returned mostly degenerate results because many metrics have p95==0; meaningful metric faults (finite p95 breaches >1.5) were not found for MG nodes. Log analysis showed a notable GC pause spike on Tomcat04 at 14:08 (log.gc_pause_max exceeded p95 by ~1.44x) and smaller GC increases on Tomcat03/Tomcat01. What can be derived so far: the failure window contains (a) an early trace spike on Tomcat03 at ~14:08, (b) major MG01/MG02 trace degradations starting ~14:09 and recurring ~14:19, and (c) a GC pause on Tomcat04 at ~14:08. These observations produce two competing hypotheses for root cause: (1) a Tomcat-level JVM/GC issue (Tomcat03 or Tomcat04) started ~14:08 and propagated to MG traces; (2) MG01/MG02 suffered routing/service-level overload starting ~14:09 causing downstream trace latency. To decide, we need exact timestamps and values for the Tomcat trace spikes and the Tomcat GC/log events to determine which component fault started first and whether JVM metrics (GC, memory, CPU) coincide with the earliest trace spike. Currently the root cause is not definitive.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the incident-window tables already stored in kernel variables, retrieve compact timepoint data to disambiguate order and cause: (1) From window_trace, select rows for component Tomcat03 where trace_name contains 'trace.self' (include duration_mean and duration_p95) and return columns (component, trace_name, timestamp, value), sorted by timestamp ascending, limit 20 rows. (2) From window_log, select rows for components Tomcat03 and Tomcat04 where log_name is one of ['log.gc_pause_max','log.row_count','log.error_count'], return columns (component, log_name, timestamp, value), sorted by timestamp ascending, limit 40 rows. Store results in kernel variables tomcat3_self_traces_window and tomcat3_4_logs_window and return the two compact tables." }

{
    "analysis": "What has been done: You computed global thresholds, filtered telemetry to the incident window (2021-03-10 14:00–14:30 UTC+8), detected anomalies and fault runs. Trace analysis found strong latency spikes in MG01/MG02 (notably at ~14:09 and ~14:19) and an earlier Tomcat-level trace spike for Tomcat03 (14:02–14:06). Metric-level analysis for MG nodes did not reveal meaningful finite-p95 resource faults (most metric anomalies were degenerate p95==0 cases). Log analysis showed a modest GC pause spike on Tomcat04 at 14:08 and small GC increases on Tomcat03/Tomcat01. What can be derived: there are two plausible scenarios — a Tomcat JVM/GC issue (Tomcat03 or Tomcat04) beginning ~14:02–14:08 that propagated to MG traces, or an MG-level overload/failure starting ~14:09 that caused downstream latency. We have temporal evidence: Tomcat03 trace.self latency spikes occur earlier (14:02–14:06) than the main MG spikes (~14:09). Tomcat04 shows a GC pause at 14:08 (close to MG spike). However, metric resource faults with clear breaches for Tomcat nodes (e.g., heap exhaustion, CPU spike, OOM) were not yet confirmed. Next we must inspect Tomcat JVM/host resource metrics (heap usage, GC pause, CPU, threads) within the incident window to see if a resource event on Tomcat03 or Tomcat04 preceded the MG trace spikes and could be the root cause.",
