}

{
    "analysis": "What has been done: We computed global thresholds, filtered telemetry to the incident window (2021-03-10 14:00–14:30 UTC+8), ran anomaly detection and fault identification on metrics, traces, and logs. Trace analysis revealed strong latency/row_count anomalies on MG01 and MG02 concentrated at ~14:09 and again ~14:19; Tomcat03 exhibited an earlier trace.self latency spike between ~14:02–14:06. Metric-level fault detection for MG and Tomcat components produced mostly degenerate results due to many series having p95==0; meaningful finite-p95 metric faults were not found that clearly precede the MG trace spikes. Log analysis found a modest GC pause on Tomcat04 at ~14:08 and small GC increases on Tomcat03/Tomcat01, but no error_count spikes. What can be derived so far: temporal ordering suggests Tomcat-level trace latency (Tomcat03) occurred earlier (~14:02–14:06) than the main MG spikes (~14:09), and Tomcat04 shows a GC pause at ~14:08 (close to MG spike). However, there is no clear metric evidence (CPU/heap/GC) that a Tomcat JVM resource event caused the MG spikes. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next decisive step is focused trace-level inspection in the early spike window to determine which service (MG or downstream Tomcat) is observed as faulty within the call chains at the moment the MG anomalies begin — specifically, we must extract trace anomaly records around the first MG spike to identify the most downstream faulty service in those traces and the precise first anomaly timestamp to attribute root cause.",
