    "analysis": "What has been done: We computed global P95 thresholds, filtered telemetry to the incident window (2021-03-10 14:00–14:30 UTC+8), and performed anomaly detection on metrics, traces, and logs. Trace analysis revealed earliest, consistent signal of increased load: MG01/MG02 trace row_count to dockerA/B services rose at ~14:00–14:01, preceding larger duration_p95 spikes around ~14:09 and additional spikes ~14:19. Tomcat03 had an earlier self-trace latency spike (14:02–14:06), and Tomcat04 showed a modest GC pause at ~14:08, but metric-level faults with clear finite-p95 breaches on MG nodes were not yet found. What can be derived: the temporal ordering indicates MG row_count increases at ~14:00–14:01 are the earliest observable anomalies; these likely reflect increased request routing or throughput which later corresponded to latency spikes. To choose the root cause we must determine whether MG nodes experienced a resource fault (CPU, network, JVM, disk) at the start, or whether an upstream load/routing change caused MG to see more traffic (i.e., root cause upstream). Next step: inspect MG01 and MG02 host/JVM metrics within the incident window to see if any resource KPI peaked at or before the initial row_count increase (14:00–14:01) with a significant breach vs baseline (p95 or median).",
